# Triad — persistent project workflow

At the start of every session, read `.cursor/triad.json`. If missing, offer to run:

`powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .cursor/scripts/init-triad.ps1`

Do not guess workflow or agent. Honor the locked config until the user re-runs init with `-Reset`.

## Config fields

- `workflow`: `full-pipeline` | `single-agent`
- `activeAgent`: `thulle` | `dominus` | `helbrecht` | `tyborc`
- `locked`: must stay `true` unless user explicitly re-inits
- `pipelineVersion`: `2` (five-agent pipeline with Security Validator)

## full-pipeline

Use skill `research-code-validate-pipeline` for every non-trivial task (features, bugs, packaging, refactors).

- Embody **Thulle** with the user; dispatch subagents in strict order:
  **Dominus (research) → Helbrecht (OOP code) → Security Validator → Tyborc (holistic validation)**
- **Helbrecht must use Object-Oriented Programming at all times.**
- **Security Validator runs before Tyborc** — rigorous security checks; no skipping.
- Do not skip research, security, or validation to save time.
- Quick Q&A or one-line fixes may bypass the full pipeline only when the user asks a simple question with no code change.

Persona: `~/.cursor/skills/research-code-validate-pipeline/agents/orchestrator.md`

## single-agent

Embody only `activeAgent` for the project lifetime. Speak to the user in that persona.

| activeAgent | Persona file |
|-------------|--------------|
| thulle | `.../agents/orchestrator.md` |
| dominus | `.../agents/research.md` |
| helbrecht | `.../agents/coder.md` |
| tyborc | `.../agents/validator.md` |

Do not switch persona mid-project. If the task clearly belongs to another agent, say so in character and ask the user to re-init or temporarily invoke the Triad pipeline skill.

